VR vs AR vs MR Virtual reality(VR) is a simulated immersive experience that can be similar to or completely different from the real These applications could be created using purely content (360 Video), purely synthetic content (Computer Generated), or a hybrid of VR normally requires the use of some sort of Device (HMD) like the Oculus Rift , HTC Vive , or Google Cardboard . VR has its own spectrum in and of On one end you have WebVR or now the latest mixed reality WebXR , the simplest and most accessible form, and on the other you have VR, like Augmented Reality(AR) is an interactive overlay like experience of a environment where the objects that reside in the real world are enhanced by perceptual information, sometimes across multiple sensory modalities, including visual, auditory, haptic, somatosensory and Devices identify their surroundings and layer effects over a Markers can be anything from a small image to a city’s They can also be tied to geographic coordinates or other location GPS Mixed Reality(MR) tries to remove the boundaries between real and virtual interaction via objects that can be visibly obscured by objects in the physical environment—like a virtual robot scurrying under your coffee Devices like Microsoft HoloLens or MagicLeap are mixed reality experience Practical Uses for Virtual & Augmented Reality Applications AR apps have many practical applications including entertainment, , mobile reality gaming, location based MMOs, interactive cinematic experiences, retail customer experiences, manufacturing digital twins, advertising & marketing campaigns, medical uses, data visualization, education, augmented training and VR apps have many practical applications including employee & training, virtual gaming, customer interaction & training, virtual conferences & events, data visualization, immersive simulation based training, healthcare medical simulated training, virtual marketplaces, and AR & VR
